# Component-Based Slide Generation Walkthrough

I have successfully transitioned the application to a component-based architecture ("Headless Slides") and addressed key user feedback regarding images, control, and aesthetics.

## Changes Implemented

### 1. New Data Model & Types
- Updated [SlideLayout](file:///c:/Users/ADMIN/Desktop/ai_slideshow/src/types/index.ts#1-13) to support new master layouts: `hero`, `grid`, `timeline`, `split`, `metric`, `quote`.
- Extended [SlideContent](file:///c:/Users/ADMIN/Desktop/ai_slideshow/src/types/index.ts#14-53) to support flexible props like `items`, `steps`, `stats`, and `quote`.

### 2. Premium "Elastic" Components (UI Polish)
I have applied a "Top-Tier" design aesthetic (inspired by Apple/Stripe) to all master layouts:
-   **HeroSlide**: Added decorative gradient meshes, smart typography scaling (6xl-9xl), and elegant subtitle tracking.
-   **GridSlide**: Implemented card-based layouts with `shadow-xl`, rounded corners (`rounded-[2rem]`), and dynamic grid sizing.
-   **TimelineSlide**: Created a sleek horizontal flow with floating step nodes, shadow effects, and connecting lines.
-   **SplitSlide**: Enhanced with a "floating" image container, deep shadows, and refined whitespace.
-   **MetricSlide**: Uses massive ("14rem") gradient text for numbers to create high-impact data visualizations.
-   **QuoteSlide**: Features classical serif typography for quotes, elegant positioning of oversized quotation marks, and polished citation styles.

### 3. AI Service & Image Pipeline Updates
-   **Image Fixing**: Restored the `crawlSourceForImages` service in [gemini.ts](file:///c:/Users/ADMIN/Desktop/ai_slideshow/src/services/gemini.ts).
-   **Grounding Toggle**: Added a user-controlled "Google Grounding" toggle in the Toolbar.
-   **Logic**: The [generateSlides](file:///c:/Users/ADMIN/Desktop/ai_slideshow/src/services/gemini.ts#28-136) function now accepts a `useGrounding` flag. If enabled, it searches the web, crawls distinct sources, and uses a second AI pass ("Fusion") to intelligently assign relevant images to slides.

